statement.p:
The multiple integral of a function f on the cube \mathcal{C} is the limit

                \idotsint_\mathcal{C} f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) \,  \tder{}{\textnormal{V}} = \lim_{\|\mathcal{P}\| \to 0} RS_{\mathcal{P}}

            if it exists. If the limit exists, we say that f is integrable on \mathcal{C}.

Let f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) be defined on the n-cube \mathcal{C} = [a_1, b_1] \times \cdots \times [a_n , b_n]. The integral of f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) with respect to the i-th variable is the function 

                F (t_1, \ldots, t_{i -1}, t_{i + 1} , \ldots , t_n) := \int_{a_i}^{b_i} f(t_1, \ldots, t_{i - 1}, x_i, t_{i + 1}, \ldots,  t_n) \, \tder{}{x_i} 

            on the (n - 1)-cube \mathcal{C} (i). We say that f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) is integrable with respect to x_i if the integral of f(x_1, \ldots, x_n) with respect to the i-th variable exists.

Let 
                        f(x,y,z) = xy -  \frac{z}{x}
                       and \mathcal{C} = [-3, 2] \times [1, 4] \times [0, 2]. Calculate the integral of f(x,y,z) with respect to the variables x, y and z as functions of (y,z), (x, z) and (x,y) respectively.
